solution.p:
 (a) The capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor is given by

	 C \amp = \dfrac{\epsilon_0\:A}{d}
	 \amp = \dfrac{8.85\times 10^{-12}\: \text{F/m}\times (0.2\:\text{m} \times 0.2\:\text{m} )}{0.002\:\text{m}} 
	 \amp  = 177\:\text{pF}.

(a)	Using the formula for the capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor with a dielctric we get

	 C \amp = K\:\dfrac{\epsilon_0\:A}{d}
	 \amp = 7\times \dfrac{8.85\times 10^{-12}\:\textrm{F/m}\times 0.06\:\textrm{m}^2}{0.004\:\textrm{m}} = 0.93\: \textrm{nF}.

(a) Using the formula for the capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor filled with a dielectric we get

	 C \amp = \epsilon_r\:\dfrac{\epsilon_0\:A}{d} 
	 \amp = 3.7\times \dfrac{8.85\times 10^{-12}\:\textrm{F/m}\times 0.0625\:\textrm{m}^2}{0.0002\:\textrm{m}} = 10.2\: \textrm{nF}.

(b)	Polarization depends on the electric field in the dielectric, i.e., paper here, which is related to the electric field in vacuum through the dielectric constant.

	 P \amp = \epsilon_0\: (\epsilon_r-1)\: E
	 \amp  = \epsilon_0\: (\epsilon_r-1)\: \dfrac{E_0}{\epsilon_r}
	 \amp = \dfrac{\epsilon_0\: (\epsilon_r-1)}{\epsilon_r}\:\dfrac{Q/A}{\epsilon_0},
	 \amp = \dfrac{ \epsilon_r-1}{\epsilon_r}\:\dfrac{Q}{A}

Putting the numbers in the expression we find

	 P \amp = \dfrac{3.7-1}{3.7}\:\dfrac{50\times 10^{-6}\:\textrm{C}}{0.25\times0.25\:\textrm{m}^2}
	 \amp = 5.8\times 10^{-4} \text{C/m}^2.
